text.tspan: git started!
While this is far from a complete guide, here are the general steps
you'll want to take to use git.
If all of the repositories you'll be using are/will be available on
GitHub, there are desktop applications you can use. Otherwise,
you can use command line to access repositories stored just about
anywhere!
You'll need access to wherever your repository is or will be. On
GitHub or GitLab, this means having an account and having
someone add you to the project. Other repositories will have their
own repositories.
You'll want to clone an existing repository. This gives you a local
copy of the repository that you can edit before you send your
changes to the original, or origin. If one doesn't exist already, you
can start one!
If you've created any new files, you'll need to add them to the
repoository before you can commit any changes. Some desktop
apps will do this for you. Once you're ready to send your changes
to the repository, commit them! If you're working with branches,
make sure you're on the right one before you do.
IOnce you've committed all of your changes, you can push them.
This is what makes them available to other people; committing a
change doesn't necessarily let anyone else see it. If someone else
has pushed changes, you won't automatically have them! You'll
need to pull to see the changes that they've made. Be sure to do
this often to avoid merging lots of changes!
